\begin_layout Subsubsection
Work Done by an External Force
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The work done by an external force is the force multiplied by distance over
 which the force acts.
 In other words, the force only does work if the body it is pushing against
 actually moves in the direction of the applied force.
 In differential form we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta W=\vec{F}\cdot d\vec{x}\label{eq:dW=f dot dx}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 are vector quantities, but 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is a scalar quantity.
 As a reminder, the dot product appearing in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dW=f dot dx"

\end_inset

 is defined as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{A}\cdot\vec{B}=\left|\vec{A}\right|\left|\vec{B}\right|\cos\theta
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the angle between the two vectors, illustrated in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:dot product"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
