\begin_layout Subsubsection
Work Done by an Applied Pressure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another important example of work is the work done by an external force
 in changing the volume of the system that is under a state of hydrostatic
 pressure.
 The easiest and most important example to describe is a gas that is being
 compressed by a piston as shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:gas compression"

\end_inset

.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dW=f dot dx"

\end_inset

 still applies in this case, but the force in this case is given by the
 product of the area and pressure:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{F}=P\vec{A}\label{eq:F = P A}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It may seem strange to write the area as a vector, but it is just reminding
 us that the pressure acts perpendicular to the surface, so the direction
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{A}$
\end_inset

 is perpendicular to the surface of the piston.
 Combing Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:F = P A"

\end_inset

 with Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dW=f dot dx"

\end_inset

 gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta W=P\vec{A}\cdot d\vec{x}\label{eq:dW=f dot dx-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The decrease in volume of the gas is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{A}\cdot d\vec{x}$
\end_inset

, so we can replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{A}\cdot d\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $-dV$
\end_inset

 to obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta W=-PdV
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This result is an important one that we will use quite a bit later on.
\end_layout

